Another example of asymmetric acquaintance is where AGENT1 is "introduced" to AGENT2 while (the former is) in disguise and using a faked identity. If PROP is not the final step in ALGORITHM, this output might serve as an input to a subsequent step. (assertionIsArgumentFor ASSN-1 ASSN-2) means that ASSN-1 is an argument for ASSN-2. In other words, ASSN-1 is one of the assertions used in a (potential) proof for ASSN-2. So if ASSN-1 is one of 5 assertions supporting ASSN-2, (assertionIsArgumentFor ASSN-1 ASSN-2) should be true. Although this predicate could conceivably be a meta-assertion on the assertion supports for any conclusion of the inference engine, the real intent of this predicate is for the kind of entailments that only a human Cyclist would notice. In a sense assertionIsArgumentFor means that ASSN-2 is redundant. If ASSN-1 and ASSN-2 are arguments for each other or are at about the same level of generality, then use redundantAssertions. Although not currently (Feb 98) supported, assertionIsArgumentFor may help the system to narrow search. E.g. if ASSN-2 has already been used unsuccesfully in an inference path, then attempting to use ASSN-1 is less likely to be succesful. In general, marking redundant assertions, rather than removing them, increases the robustness of the knowledge. It is possible, for instance, to release redundant assertions without having to release more powerful arguments. See also subsumingAssertions.
label: Assertion Is Argument For

A predicate that relates an agent to some cotemporal thing s/he is able to control. More precisely, (ableToControl AGENT THING) means that AGENT is in a position of being able to either:

(i) influence (i.e., prohibit, enable, or constrain) some significant set of behaviors (or actions or functionings) of THING or
(ii) influence some significant set of behaviors of other agents with respect to THING.

For example, Wilbur Post might be able to control some range of his horse Ed's actions in virtue of having the (physical and legal) power to force Ed to walk down this bridle path, stay in that corral, and so on; and Wilbur might also be able to control Ed in the sense of deciding who has access to him (e.g., deciding who may see Ed and who may ride him).

The controlled THING might be a non-living possession of AGENT's or, as in the above example, another agent. Since one's ability to control something is rarely comprehensive, (ableToControl AGENT THING) can hold despite the fact there are many behaviors/actions/functionings of THING's that are beyond AGENT's control. Thus, although Wilbur might be able to control which paths Ed is ridden on, where he sleeps, and what he eats, Wilbur might not be able to control such things as Ed's breathing rate, tail swishing, or what he does in the privacy of his stall.

Note that AGENT's being ableToControl THING does not entail that AGENT actually exercises this ability. Note also that AGENT's merely being able to influence some behavior of THING (or some behavior of another agent's with respect to THING) is not sufficient for her being ableToControl THING; AGENT must be able to influence a significant set or range of THING's behaviors (or of other agents' behaviors with respect to THING) in order to be able to control THING (see influencesAgent). (Unavoidably, the notions of being "able" to do something and of a "significant range" of a thing's behaviors/actions/functionings are both rather vague.) For describing events in which an agent actually wields control over something, consider using ControllingSomething and objectControlled.
label: Able To Control
ableToControl

These two relationships often go together, of course. But it is also possible to have such authority but not use it (or be unable to), and possible to exert control without relevant authorization. For example, if PERSON1 owns THING and PERSON2 steals it, then PERSON1 retains the (legal) authority to control THING, but actual control passes to PERSON2. The 'authority' expressed by this predicate often has a legal basis, as in the case of ownership. But certain other sources may also confer authority. For example, such authority might attach to a certain position within an organization (i.e., be recognized within the organization), even if that authority is not legally enforceable (in fact, even if the organization is illegal, e.g., a criminal organization).

comment:
An ActorSlot and a specialization of animateDoer and nonDeliberateActors (qq.v.). The predicate bodilyDoer relates a given physical event to any organism that is a non-deliberate "doer" of the event (i.e. the organism acts without conscious intention or volition). (bodilyDoer EVENT DOER) means that DOER does EVENT (which entails that DOER is not merely subjected to EVENT by external forces), but does it non-deliberately.

Note that for certain kinds of actions (e.g. physical growth, peristalsis, and reflex actions) organisms are always merely bodilyDoers; for certain other actions (e.g. breathing, flinching, and shouting) an organism commonly acts as a bodilyDoer, but sometimes acts instead as a deliberate performer (see performedBy).

Note also that an organism that dies of natural causes is the bodilyDoer of that event, because of the internal processes the body does during its Dying. And in certain PhysiologicalConditions, including an AilmentCondition (e.g. diabetes) or a healing process, organisms are considered to be bodilyDoers because their own bodily processes are creating or sustaining those conditions. An organism killed by an external agent, however, is just a bodilyActedOn (q.v.) actor in that event; thus instances of KillingByOrganism should use bodilyActedOn to describe the organism killed.
label: bodily doer
bodilyDoer

In other cases, the further condition is that NOMINEE win an election in which s/he competes against other nominees for the same position; if s/he wins, NOMINEE becomes an elected member of ORG (see electedToOrganization).

For example, (relationAllInstance agentNominatesMembersOfOrg IranianHeadOfJudiciary IranianGuardianCouncil) means that the Head of Judiciary in Iran may nominate members to the Guardian Council. The "appropriate circumstances" for this obtain every three years, when the terms of three of the six lay members of the Guardian Council end. Let ORDER be a TotalOrdering_Strict, and let S be the baseSet of ORDER and R the ordering relation. ORDER is a WellOrdering if every nonempty subset SUBSET of S has its 'R-smallest' member, i.e., there is an X in SUBSET such that R(X Y) for all Y in SUBSET except X. The predicate addressText_NC maps a particular element of ContactLocation to a non-canonical #$Address-LocationDesignator, ADDRESS. The `NC' in the name stands for `non-canonical'. (addressText_NC LOCATION ADDRESS) means that the ContactLocation LOCATION has the non-canonicalized address ADDRESS. For example, one value for addressText_NC of the Cycorp MailingLocation is `Cycorp, 3721 Executive Center Dr., Ste. 100, Austin, TX 78731-1615.' Note that this address as printed does not conform to the US Postal Service's recommended standard for printed addresses, and so relative to this standard it is not `canonical.' Non-canonical means that ADDRESS may not conform to the canonicalization scheme(s) used for other known addresses for LOCATION. These other (presumed canonical) addresses should be related to LOCATION using the predicate addressText. It really only makes sense to use addressText_NC in contexts (such as the logical schemas for certain database tables) where LOCATION may have both canonical and non-canonical addresses entered for it. In contexts where the differences between canonicalized and non-canonicalized addresses is not an issue, just use addressText. See also ContactLocation.
